{"title":{"rendered":"Banana Tree (Musa acuminata)"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><a href=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-7818\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana-1024x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"840\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana-150x150.jpg 150w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana-300x300.jpg 300w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana-768x768.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana-1200x1200.jpg 1200w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/01204623/Sorabjee_banana.jpg 1331w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /></a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">For those who’ve grown up between those blessed latitudes that define the tropics, any sight of a banana plant, with its spaniel ears flopping in the breeze, is a homecoming. The banana plant of my childhood produced bouquets of four-inch fruits; its flowers were best consumed in a Bengali curry; its leathery leaves became plates at weddings and remain the greatest vessel for steaming fish — or anything, really. If Barragan had his pink watermelon glowing under a tarp, I will have my luminous banana plant, its shade tinged with a blissful tropical garden.</p>\n"},"meta":{"contributors":[{"title":{"rendered":"Maya Sorabjee"},"slug":"maya-sorabjee","meta":{"degree":"M.Arch I","graduation_year":"2020"}}],"fold":{"title":{"rendered":"Trees for the Forest"},"slug":"trees","meta":{"volume":"5","number":"17","bulletin":false,"publication_date":"2020-04-02"}}}}